value.0: This woman bears no mark or insignia on her old-style vestments, but possesses an air of superiority.

A tall, waspish woman with sharp features and a piercing gaze. Her skin is the color of angry storm clouds, and ebony hair hangs thinly in front of her face, the ends trailing off into wispy smoke. Her eyes are pools of solid color, pure black and swirling malevolently. 
Reinforced clerical robes hang limply off her elongated limbs, and do little to mask her almost skeletal physique. A pair of matte black chakram hang off a hook at her hip, and she seems to radiate an air of unmistakable power. Her movements are languid and fluid, and her will almost impossible to ignore should she favour you with a gaze.
Tired of all those pesky Paladins twarting your delicioulsy evil plots? Well, this robe might be the answer!

A silver plaque is mounted on the top center of the picture frame. The finely italicized engraving reads, <c >Inspired by the poem, 'Roses and Dust'. The first work work in the collection 'Full Circle'.</c>
  
This oil painting looks to be rather simple. The details seem to be blurred and hazy, as if it is not something seen, but more likely something remembered. The most prevalent color on the canvas is a rusty gray tone. A woman stands in a temple, past the rows of benches. She looks sunken and thin, her brown hair arranged in a bun atop her head with a veil attached, she looks almost as though she has fallen asleep standing up.

In her hand is a bouquet of dried out and mutilated wildflowers, her half lidded eyes stare down the aisle. She is dressed in a dark blue gown that has some small holes in the skirt, where you can see her paled skin. Beside her a crown lays on the ground, cobwebs forming around the circlet. The entire scene looks silent and stale.

The bottom left corner of the painting has lyrics painted in stark white:
<c >Dark clouds circle like starved vultures
Distant echoes of thunder
Silken fabric has gathered mud and debris
The crown cast aside
We were meant to walk down an aisle of orchids and roses
But life in you fades as dust fills our noses</c>

A silver plaque is mounted on the top center of the picture frame. The finely italicized engraving reads, <c >Inspired by the 'A Tenuous Thread'. The second work in the collection 'Full Circle'.</c>
   
This oil painting is mostly black in color, with a spotlight effect only on the center of the painting. The light reveals a woman, perched on a throne pridefully. She has dusky skin and dark hair with white streaks that falls in plaits past her waist, her lips are almost too red as they pull into a slight sneer. She cups the bottom of a wine glass, not bothering to hold it by the stem. The liquid seems to be wine, but perhaps too bright for that. She seems to stare at the seeming source of the light with narrowed eyes.
At the foot of a throne and androgynous figure kneels. The shadowed figure is holding her wrist face up with one hand, and the other hand is reaching for her glass.
 
The bottom left corner of the painting has lyrics painted in stark white:
<c >I never could have foreseen This drastic fall from grace
A lifetime of darkness Has lead me to this place
I thirst for the forbidden Parched for the taste
I seek my inner calm Neglect all thought of haste</c>

A silver plaque is mounted on the top center of the picture frame. The finely italicized engraving reads, <c >Inspired by the song 'Perfect Cannot Save Us'. The third work in the collection 'Full Circle'.</c>
  
This oil painting is painted in monochrome colors, the painting looking washed out and unsaturated. In the middle of the canvas a grand dining table is set up for a grand feast, though despite the array of wine bottles and food there are only two chairs on either end of the long table. In one chair, a man sits, finely dressed, his long white hair combed back perfectly. His plate is full of food, but he is posed with his hands folded on the edge of the table, staring vacantly. He has an angular look to him, looking more like a mannequin then a real human.

On the other end of the table, a woman sits with an unnervingly pleasant smile on her features, also looking stiff and posed similarly to the man. However, behind her, almost as though it has crawled out of the woman is a figure of a similar size and shape to her. The dark unseelie-esque figure has large purple wings, the most vibrant part of the painting, and her face is formed into a deep scowl. Her overly large black eyes stare hatefully at the man, her claws digging into the smooth flesh of the woman's shoulders, poised to attack.

The bottom left corner of the painting has lyrics painted in stark white:
<c >Perfect cannot save them, worry spreads like disease
Silence consumes her heart again
Cannot feel a thing... Cannot feel a thing...
The dim light of this flame dies, though he's begging please
Nothing makes sense anymore
Cannot even sing... Cannot even sing...</c>

A silver plaque is mounted on the top center of the picture frame. The finely italicized engraving reads, <c >Inspired by the poem 'Solitude'. The fourth work in the collection 'Full Circle'.</c>
 
This oil panting was painted with a fine brush, the canvas completely gray with two ivory figures in the center and white luminescent dots lingering in the background like fireflies.

The scene depicts the back of a woman as she sits upon a finely crafted stool, gazing into a full length mirror. Her fingers are on the glass, touching her reflection and where the fingers meet a small stream of blood originates rolling down the surface of the painting.

The woman's hair is fair in color and thick, pulled into a neat bun atop her head, adorned with an expensive pearl comb. The few tendrils of hair not upswept cascade down her back in perfectly uniform curls. Her dress is white, just a shade or two lighter than her skin, the top is made of form-fitting silken fabric buttons in the back of the gown reach all the way to the nape of her neck, and the skirt of the dress is layers upon layers of white gossamer, gathered around her legs and feet.

The posture of the woman is overly perfect, rigid. The only softness apparent is the position of her hand on the mirror, and the one resting upon her lap. Her expression is one of scrutiny and wonder, her pale pink lips parted in what looks like a soft gasp. Her pallid eyes are wide as she meets the eyes of her reflection, and her eyebrows drawn together.

The bottom left corner of the painting has lyrics painted in stark white:
<c >A pinprick, blood blossoms
Runs down the reflection 
Was this how it was once?
To be close was to be harmed 
Disbelieving eyes meet mine 
This. The price of my vanity</c>

Crafted from the finest polished obsidian, this dark altar glints in the dim lighting of the temple. There is a silken cloth draped upon the altar with great care, the shimmering fabric undulating at the slightest draft. The bare edges of the altar that are not covered in fabric have carvings etched into the surface, barely visible.
 
On the left side of the altar there is a thick circle engraved into the obsidian, and inside the circle is the silhouette of a nude and curvaceous woman. The woman is arced gracefully, her hands outstretched above her long mane of hair as she seems to dance.

On the right side of the altar there is another thickly engraved circle, and inside the circle there is the depiction of a woman in heavy silken robe, her body language subdued, upon her face is a mask of feathers and her lips are parted as if to sing or speak.

In the middle of the altar, on the side closest to the wall, the silken fabric is pulled forward to reveal a third carving. This thick circle contains the clear etching of an hourglass, standing upright and utterly empty.
